body:
So I looked into wrapping errors some more.  Intuition told me that having a custom Error class would be the _right_ way to do it.  It turns out the `Error` class in Javascript is a strange beast.  Both `Error('text')` and `new Error('text')` return new instances of an Error object.  This is because the `Error` constructor doesn't actually act on `this`.  This, no pun intended, makes inheritance tricky.  I wrote the following snipped which seems to do the trick:

``` javascript
var WrapError = function(message, error){

    // The Error class doesn't actually act on `this`.  Instead it always
    // returns a new instance of Error.  Here we capture that instance so we
    // can apply it's properties to `this`.
    var tmp = Error.apply(this, [message]);

    // Copy the properties of the error over to this.
    var properties = Object.getOwnPropertyNames(tmp);
    for (var i = 0; i < properties.length; i++) {
        this[properties[i]] = tmp[properties[i]];
    }

    // Keep a stack of the original error messages.
    if (error instanceof WrapError) {
        this.error_stack = error.error_stack;
    } else {
        this.error_stack = [error];
    }
    this.error_stack.push(tmp);

    return this;
};
WrapError.prototype = Object.create(Error.prototype, {});
```
